item.title: Gold Edges Higher Amid Wait-And-See Mood Before U.S. Data
item.description: Gold edged higher in early Asian trade with the market in a wait-and-see mood ahead of upcoming U.S. economic data.

item.title: Oil Inches Lower as Chinese Economic Worries Persist
item.description: Oil prices edged lower as concerns lingered about what a weak Chinese economy would mean for demand, and as investors awaited U.S. crude stock figures from the API.

item.title: Investors Look Confident That Dollar Will Weaken Further
item.description: The dollar hit another 15-month low against the euro, and UniCredit Research said low volatility suggests investors are confident the currency can weaken further.

item.title: Ocado Beating Ebitda, Cash-Flow Views Delivers Positive Sentiment
item.description: Ocado beat Ebitda and cash-flow forecasts in its first-half results, and despite it reiterating its overly ambitious midterm target, sentiment around the print is positive, RBC Capital Markets said, keeping an underperform rating with a 460-pence price target.

item.title: Ten-Year US, German Bond Yields Seen Moving Sideways in Coming Months
item.description: The 10-year Treasury and German Bund yields are expected to trend sideways in the coming months, albeit with some volatility, but to fall on a one-year horizon, DZ Bank Research said.

item.title: Ocado Keeps Outlook After Swing to Profit
item.description: Ocado reiterated its 2023 targets after reporting underlying earnings of £16.6 million for the first half of the year but a widened pretax loss.

item.title: Ten-Year US, German Bond Yields Seen Moving Sideways in Coming Months
item.description: The 10-year Treasury and German Bund yields are expected to trend sideways in the coming months, albeit with some volatility, but to fall on a one-year horizon, DZ Bank Research said.

item.title: Vodafone to Receive Further Vantage Payment
item.description: Vodafone said it will receive €500 million from a consortium of investors led by Global Infrastructure Partners and KKR as part of the partnership agreement for Vantage Towers.

item.title: Casino Approves Talks With Kretinsky Group
item.description: Casino has agreed to continue talks with a consortium led by Czech billionaire Daniel Kretinsky over a plan to inject €1.2 billion in new equity into the retailer, after a rival team ended negotiations over a rescue package.

item.title: Tele2 Lifts Guidance After Profit Beat
item.description: Tele2 posted a 2% rise in second-quarter underlying earnings and a higher-than-expected net profit and slightly upgraded its service revenue growth targets.

item.title: SEB Profit Tops Forecasts on Net Interest Income Strength
item.description: SEB posted an increased net profit of SEK9.8 billion in the second quarter as net interest income rose 53%, but said that part of the transitory strength it has seen in net interest income “was behind it.”

item.title: Novartis Upgrades Outlook After Strong First Half
item.description: Novartis said it expected core operating income to grow in the low double digits from a previous expectation of high-single-digit growth, lifted its sales guidance and confirmed its $15 billion share buyback.

item.title: Taiwan's Vice President Plans Stop in the U.S. at a Delicate Moment
item.description: Taiwan’s vice president plans to visit the U.S. in August, less than five months after a similar visit by the island democracy’s president sparked an angry response from Beijing.

item.title: Beijing Launches Policies to Boost Consumption---But Not Major Stimulus
item.description: Chinese authorities released a set of policies to bolster domestic consumption—but the moves fell short of major stimulus, underscoring Beijing’s limited options to jump-start sputtering economic growth.

item.title: Australian Banks' Deposits Battle to Intensify
item.description: Heightened competition between Australian banks for deposits is likely to continue amid a range of funding pressures, said Bank of Queensland’s general manager of everyday banking and deposits.

item.title: China Plans to Build a Satellite Network to Rival Elon Musk's Starlink
item.description: China plans to launch thousands of broadband satellites into low-Earth orbit to bring hundreds of millions online and sell connections across the globe. But doing so will pit it against SpaceX’s Starlink. WSJ explores how China can compete in this crowded stretch of space.

item.title: The Man Charged With Steering the Yuan Through China's Economic Turmoil
item.description: Pan Gongsheng has experience in high-stakes tasks, but China’s fragile economy raises new risks.

item.title: Taylor Swift became the first woman overall and first living artist in nearly six decades to have four albums on Billboard's top 10 list in a single week, according to the magazine.
item.description: Taylor Swift became the first woman overall and first living artist in nearly six decades to have four albums on Billboard’s top 10 list in a single week, according to the magazine.

item.title: Major U.S. stock indexes posted gains, with the S&P 500, Nasdaq and Dow industrials advancing 0.4%, 0.9% and 0.2%, respectively.
item.description: Major U.S. stock indexes posted gains, with the S&P 500, Nasdaq and Dow industrials advancing 0.4%, 0.9% and 0.2%, respectively.

item.title: Biden spoke with Netanyahu and the leaders agreed to meet in the U.S. later this year, working to ease tensions as the administration and some Democrats have criticized moves by Israel's right-wing government.
